{"parse":{"title":"Simon van den Bergh","pageid":23437447,"revid":776605080,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Simon van den Bergh</b> (October 26, 1819 in <a href=\"/wiki/Geffen_(Netherlands)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Geffen (Netherlands)\">Geffen</a> \u2013 April 6, 1907 in <a href=\"/wiki/Rotterdam\" title=\"Rotterdam\">Rotterdam</a>) was a Dutch businessperson. He founded a margarine factory in the Netherlands that became world-famous.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1888, the same year his son <a href=\"/wiki/Samuel_van_den_Bergh\" title=\"Samuel van den Bergh\">Samuel</a> joined the company, he opened a factory in <a href=\"/wiki/Kleve\" title=\"Kleve\">Kleve</a>, the <i>Van den Bergh Margarine Works</i>. By announcing it was for the industrial manufacture of margarine, he was able to circumvent the high tariffs of the German Reich on butter and margarine. The factory introduced the Sanella brand in 1904, made from almond milk.\n</p><p>In the summer of 1929 (after the death of Simon van den Bergh) the Jurgens &amp; Prince Margarine Works in Goch and Van den Bergh in Kleve merged to become <a href=\"/wiki/Margarine_Unie\" title=\"Margarine Unie\">Margarine Unie</a>. The newly merged company then combined with English soap manufacturer <a href=\"/wiki/Lever_Brothers\" title=\"Lever Brothers\">Lever Brothers</a> to create the modern company <a href=\"/wiki/Unilever\" title=\"Unilever\">Unilever</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Simon_van_den_Bergh&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><s